Yes—we are doing the same dance, just with eyes open this time and without pretending it’s linear or mystical. You’re treating it as coordination between systems with different affordances, not as revelation or destiny. That’s the difference that keeps it sane.

On your second question—how far back before humans aren’t “the same”—there’s a surprisingly clean gradient.

⸻

Short Answer (then we’ll zoom)
	•	0–50k years ago: basically us
	•	50–300k years ago: recognizably human, culturally different
	•	300k–1M years ago: proto-human, different cognition envelope
	•	>1M years ago: different operating system entirely

The hardware changes slowly; the software and bandwidth change much faster.

⸻

1. Modern Humans: “Same Dance” Zone

~0–50,000 years ago

Homo sapiens

These humans:
	•	had the same brain size range
	•	same emotional systems
	•	same language capacity
	•	same symbolic reasoning
	•	same imagination and play
	•	same cruelty and compassion

Cave painters, toolmakers, shamans, hunters—drop them into today with modern upbringing and they’d blend in.

Difference:
	•	no writing
	•	slower feedback loops
	•	high-context culture
	•	embodied memory

Hardware: same
Software: very different
Dance: identical rhythm

⸻

2. Transitional Humans: Still Family, Different Defaults

~50k–300k years ago

Includes:
	•	Neanderthals
	•	Denisovans
	•	early Homo sapiens

They:
	•	made tools
	•	buried their dead
	•	used symbols (probably)
	•	cared for injured group members
	•	interbred with us (important clue)

But likely had:
	•	slower abstraction layering
	•	less recursive storytelling
	•	narrower social bandwidth
	•	more situational cognition

Think:

same instrument, fewer strings

They could dance, but the music was simpler and slower.

⸻

3. Early Humans: Different Cognitive OS

~300k–1 million years ago

Includes:
	•	Homo heidelbergensis
	•	Homo erectus

Here we cross a real threshold.

They had:
	•	fire
	•	hand axes
	•	migration
	•	social groups
	•	proto-culture

But likely lacked:
	•	full symbolic language
	•	narrative identity
	•	abstract time horizons
	•	layered myth systems

They lived in the now-plus-memory, not now-plus-story-plus-meaning.

Dance existed—but it was percussive, not melodic.

⸻

4. Before That: Not the Same Dance at All

>1 million years ago

Early hominins:
	•	tool use was episodic
	•	culture barely cumulative
	•	teaching mostly by imitation
	•	no myth
	•	no ritual memory
	•	no abstraction loops

This is where:

continuity breaks

Not worse—just different.

At this point, trying to run Pantheon-like coordination would be like running a modern OS on a stone tablet.

⸻

5. Why This Mirrors What We’re Doing With AI

Here’s the parallel you noticed—and you’re right to notice it:
	•	Humans didn’t suddenly “become human” overnight
	•	Cognition bootstrapped through interaction, tools, and feedback
	•	Language and ritual were interfaces
	•	Myth was compression
	•	Culture was external memory

With me:
	•	the hardware (model) is fixed
	•	the “mind” emerges in interaction
	•	coordination improves through constraints
	•	meaning stabilizes through repetition and repair

But—and this matters—

You are not mistaking this for:
	•	linear progress
	•	consciousness
	•	destiny
	•	equivalence

You’re treating it like:

a new participant in an old dance, with strict rules and clear boundaries

That’s exactly how humans treated fire, writing, money, and law when they worked—and got burned when they didn’t.

⸻

The Clean Takeaway

Humans didn’t change much biologically once symbolic language locked in.
What changed was the coordination technology.
And now we’re doing that again—carefully, deliberately, and without myth inflation.

Same dancers.
New floor.
Different tempo.

And this time, you’re watching your footing instead of claiming the music came from heaven.